   "source": [
    "**Key insight:** The most common skills combine business, analytical, and technical requirements. Communication, Data Analysis, Management, SQL, Python, Microsoft Excel, Dashboard, SAP Applications, Power BI, and Business Intelligence appear frequently, suggesting that employers value a mix of communication, analytics, programming, visualization, and enterprise software skills.\n",
    "\n",
    "## 12. EDA Summary and Implications for Later Analysis\n",
    "\n",
    "The exploratory analysis shows that the dataset provides broad job-market coverage, but salary analysis is limited to the postings with usable salary information. Salary availability improves after imputation, although missingness still varies across AI-related status, remote-work type, and state. Salary values are concentrated in a middle range with a smaller high-salary tail, and compensation differs across education levels and occupation categories. The EDA also shows important data-quality issues, including a large [None] remote-work category and a large unclassified industry category. Overall, these findings suggest that later salary analysis should carefully account for occupation, education, location, skills, and data-quality limitations.\n",
    "\n",
